**NSForest Comparison**

Same: All 735 relationship triples and 904 edge annotations are identical. The same 5 predicates are used.

Differences:
- OLD has Binary_genes on BGS nodes, NEW has Markers — Same data, different attribute name. The old writer used #Binary_genes for the BGS annotation; the new writer uses #Markers (from the BinaryGeneSet.markers field name in the schema). Both contain the same gene lists.
- OLD has rdf#type triples (BMC instance_of SO:0001260) — The new writer doesn't emit these rdf:type triples since they're not modeled as associations in the schema.
- NEW has more vertex annotations — The new writer emits annotations for all populated entity fields (Author_cell_term, Biomarker_combination, Binary_gene_set, Expressed_genes, Species), while the old only emitted F_beta_confidence_score, Binary_genes, Markers, Total_cell_count.
- OLD has 113 extra dc#Source quintuples — The old writer emits source quintuples on the dc#Source relationship itself; the new writer doesn't double-source the source predicate.

**Mapping Comparison**

Key difference:
- OLD uses RO_0002294 (selectively_expresses), NEW uses RO_0002292 (expresses) — The old writer used a different predicate for CellType→Gene. The new writer uses the schema's CellTypeExpressesGene which maps to expresses → RO_0002292. This also means OLD has 1018 BFO_0000050 (part_of) Gene→CellType triples that the new writer doesn't produce (because Gene→CellType part_of isn't a schema association — it was a hand-coded extra in the old writer).
- NEW has many more vertex annotations — 16 attribute types vs 1 (#Cell_type), because entity fields are now fully populated.

**CELLxGENE**

- Same: 75 CSD→PUB relationships + source quintuples
- Differences: Attribute naming follows schema fields now (Organism → Species, Number_of_cells → Total_cell_count, Tissue → Anatomical_structure). OLD emits Dataset_ID, Dataset_version_ID, Collection_version_ID as separate annotations; NEW skips Dataset_version_ID (it's the term-encoded identifier) and maps the others to schema field names. NEW also filters out None function values.

**Open Targets**

- Same: 6,305 disease score edge annotations, same disease/mutation/pharmacogenetics relationships
- Differences:
  - Predicate: evaluated_in uses OPMI_0000437 (schema) vs RO_0020325 (old) — same semantic intent, different URI
  - NEW adds 3 associations: GeneMolecularlyInteractsWithDrug (RO_0002435), DrugMolecularlyInteractsWithGene (RO_0002436), and GeneGeneticallyInteractsWithGene (RO_0002435) — 119,540 new relationship triples
  - Much richer Drug annotations: OLD annotated ~4K drugs with 18 attributes; NEW annotates ~181K drug instances (per-gene drug entities) with full schema fields
  - OLD used #Synonyms, #Target, #Indications attributes not in the schema; NEW uses schema field names (Exact_synonym, Protein, etc.)

**Gene**

- Same: 4,615 Gene→Protein (produces) relationships identical
- Differences: All attribute naming follows schema fields now (Official_full_name → Label, Organism → Species, RefSeq_gene_ID → Reference_sequence_identifier, Summary → Refseq_summary, etc.). Also_known_as is now comma-joined string instead of stringified Python list. NEW adds Gene_symbol annotation. NEW has 332 more tuples from additional annotations.

**UniProt**

- Same: 4,238 Function annotations are identical
- Differences: Attribute naming follows schema fields (Protein_name → Label, Gene_name → Gene_symbol, Organism → Species, UniProt_ID skipped as term-encoded). OLD emits Function: None as a string; NEW skips None values. Annotation_score formats as 2 instead of 2.0.

**HuBMAP**

- Same: All 183 relationships + 183 source quintuples are identical (0 only in OLD)
- NEW adds: 179 #Label vertex annotations from ccf_pref_label on AnatomicalStructure entities
